summary: Another reason Rescue is so important? She’s in her 40s!
body:
Another reason Rescue is so important? She’s in her 40s!

Female heroes are NEVER allowed to mature! All our female superheroes, amazing as they are, either are in their 20s or early 30s, or at least physically appear to be so. Pepper, on the other hand, is in her mid-to-late 40s. Women don’t have expiration dates, but Hollywood often treats them as such. That is just one of many reasons the MCU needs Rescue.

summary: ————————————————————— Voicemail #20 To: Tony Stark From: Peter Parker I’ve got a report today, Mr. Stark! Before I go to sleep,...
body:
—————————————————————

Voicemail #20

To: Tony Stark

From: Peter Parker

I’ve got a report today, Mr. Stark! Before I go to sleep, I thought I’d give you a call because today was a really great day.

I stayed out late swinging around the city because Aunt May stuck at work for a bit longer than usual. I was swinging around a bit aimlessly and thinking more about my Spanish project than potential crime, to be honest. And today was so dark and rainy that I almost missed the little girl on the side of the road. But as I extended my arm to send a web to the top of the next building, I heard her crying. I dropped to the ground and turned. There was this little girl, Mr. Stark, on the side of the road with her head in her arms. She looked around five or six and she was all alone- not a single person in sight. So I walked over and crouched down next to her. She didn’t look up, just sobbed into her arms, until I whispered, “Hey”.

She jerked her head up and her eyes were all wide and scared… until she saw me. Her crying stopped a little and she said, “Spider-Man?”.

I asked her, “What’s wrong?”, and she started crying again and whimpered, “My mommy. She’s hurt”. And then she sprung up and grabbed my hand, leading me into the dark alley behind. Normally, I’m a bit scared of dark alleys but I wasn’t this time, Mr. Stark. Because this girl lead me to her mother lying in the alley- her mother with her eyes closed and face pale- and I knew I could help them, y’know? I asked Karen to look for a pulse on the woman and I asked the little girl what happened. The little girl explained that they were walking to the store when her mother collapsed and Karen confirmed that the mother was alive but needed a hospital immediately. I picked up the mother, put the little girl on my back, and I swung towards the hospital faster than any ambulance could drive.

And I made it in time, Mr. Stark, I did. The doctors told me the mother would live. I waited with the little girl at the hospital until her dad arrived- she told the doctors that she absolutely needed Spider-Man to wait with her. They tried to tell her that I had other places to be, and even though I should have been home a while ago, I told them that I could wait- no problem. And before I left, she gave me the biggest hug and whispered, “Thank you, Spider-Man”.

Y’know, sometimes I wish I never got these powers. That I was never Spider-man. But after today, I know for sure- I wouldn’t trade my life for anyone else’s. Because there’s a certain feeling I never want to miss. The feeling that you saved someone, changed their life. That you’re someone’s hero.

And that really makes all of this worth it, doesn’t it?

Whoa, sorry, that was kinda deep. I must be up too late. I probably should stop contemplating life and go to bed. Talk to you later, Mr. Stark!

—————————————————————

title: The Driving Thing
body:
read it on the AO3 at https://ift.tt/2FBf45t

by Rainsaber

Driving is serious business. So serious that Peter’s first experience on Homecoming night left him with a little bit of anxiety. Scratch that, a whole LOT of anxiety. And ignoring the problem only gets Peter as far as his eighteenth birthday where Tony is concerned. The bigger issue though is what happens to Peter when something happens to Tony. Sequel to The College Thing.
